00:47:23.930 --> 00:47:27.690
and that some of those
votes, arguably-- or that

00:47:27.690 --> 00:47:30.180
those elections, arguably--
have already not been

00:47:30.180 --> 00:47:35.010
free and fair here and
in France and in Italy.

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:38.940
And I wondered if you
had thoughts about that,

00:47:38.940 --> 00:47:46.560
and if there are structural
approaches to combating

00:47:46.560 --> 00:47:51.180
that state-sponsored
action from nation-states

00:47:51.180 --> 00:47:54.930
with an active interest in
destabilizing democracies?

00:47:54.930 --> 00:47:56.680
YASCHA MOUNK: Yeah.

00:47:56.680 --> 00:47:59.820
So look, that's
another area where

00:47:59.820 --> 00:48:03.240
I think there's all of these
weird, fruitless either/or

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:05.490
discussions, when it
can clearly be both.

00:48:05.490 --> 00:48:08.010
Sometimes, when you
look about debates,

00:48:08.010 --> 00:48:09.660
it's obviously
the Trumpist right

00:48:09.660 --> 00:48:11.632
that has an interest
in just downplaying

00:48:11.632 --> 00:48:13.590
any kind of Russian
meddling, because they just

00:48:13.590 --> 00:48:14.890
want to defend Trump.

00:48:14.890 --> 00:48:17.670
But even on the left of that,
even among people who dislike

00:48:17.670 --> 00:48:22.126
Trump, for some, there's this
weird debate between more

00:48:22.126 --> 00:48:24.000
of a center-left than
the far-left in certain

00:48:24.000 --> 00:48:27.260
incarnations, but it can
take different forms as well,

00:48:27.260 --> 00:48:28.990
where it--

00:48:28.990 --> 00:48:31.650
to caricature one
position, it's--

00:48:31.650 --> 00:48:35.089
well, Russia is the only reason
why Hillary Clinton lost,

00:48:35.089 --> 00:48:37.630
and so let's just focus on that
and everything else is great.

00:48:37.630 --> 00:48:39.830
And then on the other side,
let's not talk about Russia.

00:48:39.830 --> 00:48:41.230
All the people who want
to talk about Russia

00:48:41.230 --> 00:48:42.360
just want to talk about
Russia because they

00:48:42.360 --> 00:48:44.550
love Hillary Clinton and
don't want to-- right?

00:48:44.550 --> 00:48:46.800
And it can be both, right?

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:48.750
I mean, it's
absolutely plausible

00:48:48.750 --> 00:48:52.860
that various forms of
meddling and the data

00:48:52.860 --> 00:48:54.500
breach with Cambridge
Analytica and all

00:48:54.500 --> 00:48:57.540
of those kinds of
things may have

00:48:57.540 --> 00:48:59.970
made a difference of 80,000
votes in three states.

00:48:59.970 --> 00:49:01.860
It's very, very
difficult to test that.

00:49:01.860 --> 00:49:03.570
It's plausible that
it may have been.

00:49:03.570 --> 00:49:05.790
At the same time,
it's obviously true

00:49:05.790 --> 00:49:07.592
that even if that
hadn't happened,

00:49:07.592 --> 00:49:10.050
Donald Trump still would have
been within striking distance

00:49:10.050 --> 00:49:11.610
of winning the presidency.

00:49:11.610 --> 00:49:14.000
And if everything was fine,
if people weren't pissed off

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:16.170
at the political
system, if it had

00:49:16.170 --> 00:49:18.420
a non-populist political
candidate they were really

00:49:18.420 --> 00:49:21.630
excited about, Donald Trump
shouldn't have been anywhere

00:49:21.630 --> 00:49:23.800
within striking distance
of winning the election.

00:49:23.800 --> 00:49:27.115
So we can take the threat
of Russian meddling

00:49:27.115 --> 00:49:28.740
and other forms of
outside interference

00:49:28.740 --> 00:49:31.532
very seriously without having
to fall into the trap of saying,

00:49:31.532 --> 00:49:33.990
well, if that's the case, then
there's nothing else we need

00:49:33.990 --> 00:49:35.250
to change, right?

00:49:35.250 --> 00:49:37.780
Now, to your specific question
of what can we do about that?

00:49:37.780 --> 00:49:39.100
Well, in lots of
European countries,

00:49:39.100 --> 00:49:40.173
the answer is
really simple, which

00:49:40.173 --> 00:49:42.256
is that they don't have
the laws that America has.

00:49:42.256 --> 00:49:44.130
Until I became a citizen
about a year ago,

00:49:44.130 --> 00:49:46.680
I wasn't allowed to donate
to political campaigns.

00:49:46.680 --> 00:49:49.080
It was actually a
reasonable law, right?

00:49:49.080 --> 00:49:50.910
In Europe, there
isn't such laws.

00:49:50.910 --> 00:49:53.610
So Russian state
banks can bankroll

00:49:53.610 --> 00:49:55.215
European political parties.

00:49:55.215 --> 00:49:58.740
They usually don't do it openly,
but they do it legally, right?

00:49:58.740 --> 00:50:00.980
Well, we can change that.

00:50:00.980 --> 00:50:02.730
In the United States,
I think we can

00:50:02.730 --> 00:50:06.410
be much clearer in
investigating what's going on,

00:50:06.410 --> 00:50:10.830
obviously protecting
the Mueller probe.

00:50:10.830 --> 00:50:14.820
But also actually improving
our electoral infrastructure.

00:50:14.820 --> 00:50:18.630
It's very, very easy to hack
into our voting machines.

00:50:18.630 --> 00:50:22.320
And an outside
power can do that--

00:50:22.320 --> 00:50:25.110
in one county, change
a couple of votes

00:50:25.110 --> 00:50:27.960
around, not have an impact on
the outcome of the election,

00:50:27.960 --> 00:50:31.530
and have a huge de-legitimizing
impact on people

00:50:31.530 --> 00:50:32.980
trusting their democracy.

00:50:32.980 --> 00:50:35.970
So we need to act on that
really, really urgently,

00:50:35.970 --> 00:50:38.070
and we're not, and
that's really scary.

