00:52:23.200 --> 00:52:24.880
like the United
States, but you also

00:52:24.880 --> 00:52:26.380
have them in
parliamentary systems

00:52:26.380 --> 00:52:28.150
like Hungary and Poland.

00:52:28.150 --> 00:52:30.280
You also have them in
presidential systems.

00:52:30.280 --> 00:52:34.600
So actually, since
this similar phenomenon

00:52:34.600 --> 00:52:36.854
is going on in all kinds
of different countries

00:52:36.854 --> 00:52:38.520
that don't have a
two-party system, that

00:52:38.520 --> 00:52:40.780
don't have the
electoral college,

00:52:40.780 --> 00:52:43.690
I don't think that that's the
most important driving force,

00:52:43.690 --> 00:52:46.070
though it certainly exacerbated
the [? former ?] talk

00:52:46.070 --> 00:52:50.590
in the United States in 2016.

00:52:50.590 --> 00:52:53.590
AUDIENCE: You touched a
little bit on the impact

00:52:53.590 --> 00:52:57.190
that economic instability
can have on people's

00:52:57.190 --> 00:53:00.140
long-range viewpoints.

00:53:00.140 --> 00:53:03.177
So we've got a big rise
in automation and lots

00:53:03.177 --> 00:53:04.635
of jobs disappearing
because of it,

00:53:04.635 --> 00:53:06.200
and it's not really
going to stop.

00:53:06.200 --> 00:53:08.530
It's going to get worse.

00:53:08.530 --> 00:53:11.800
What do you think institutions
or nations or governments

00:53:11.800 --> 00:53:15.610
can do to address that
underlying instability, where

00:53:15.610 --> 00:53:17.890
we may be in a scenario
where 10%, 20%,

00:53:17.890 --> 00:53:20.530
30% of people in a
country don't have jobs,

00:53:20.530 --> 00:53:23.570
or they don't need to have jobs?

00:53:23.570 --> 00:53:24.820
YASCHA MOUNK: So a few points.

00:53:24.820 --> 00:53:28.150
First, I know that universal
basic income is something

00:53:28.150 --> 00:53:30.680
that people who work for
companies like Google

00:53:30.680 --> 00:53:32.170
like to think about.

00:53:32.170 --> 00:53:34.774
And I think there's a serious
discussion to be had there.

00:53:34.774 --> 00:53:36.190
I'm a little
politically skeptical

00:53:36.190 --> 00:53:37.810
of it, because I think
a lot of the people who

00:53:37.810 --> 00:53:39.940
vote for populists are people
who think of themselves

00:53:39.940 --> 00:53:41.690
as superior to some
other people in society.

00:53:41.690 --> 00:53:42.370
That's true of most people.

00:53:42.370 --> 00:53:43.995
We think of ourselves,
in various ways,

00:53:43.995 --> 00:53:46.900
as superior to some other people
in society, so don't judge.

00:53:46.900 --> 00:53:49.667
But they say, I'm lower-middle
class and middle class,

00:53:49.667 --> 00:53:51.250
and I'm not somebody
who's unemployed.

00:53:51.250 --> 00:53:53.650
I'm not somebody who's
working class, right?

00:53:53.650 --> 00:53:55.900
And to go to those people
and say, hey, you know what?

00:53:55.900 --> 00:53:57.910
You're probably going to lose
your job, but it's fine--

00:53:57.910 --> 00:53:59.446
because life for people at
the very bottom of society

00:53:59.446 --> 00:54:01.540
who are going to get
universal basic income

00:54:01.540 --> 00:54:03.740
is a politically difficult
conversation to have.

00:54:03.740 --> 00:54:07.600
And so I have some skepticism
about the political feasibility

00:54:07.600 --> 00:54:08.430
of that.

00:54:08.430 --> 00:54:12.240
More broadly, I think that,
look, if 50% of our jobs

00:54:12.240 --> 00:54:15.080
are just going to go away
because of automation,

00:54:15.080 --> 00:54:17.515
it's going to be very difficult
for democracy to survive.

00:54:17.515 --> 00:54:21.210
But thankfully, that
may be overblown.

00:54:21.210 --> 00:54:22.610
It may not be 50%.

00:54:22.610 --> 00:54:24.827
So in the meanwhile,
what we can do is--

00:54:24.827 --> 00:54:27.160
I'm sometimes asked about
whether I support a robot tax.

00:54:27.160 --> 00:54:29.790
And I say, no, I don't, but
I'm against the human tax.

00:54:29.790 --> 00:54:32.290
At the moment, a company that
makes a billion-dollar revenue

00:54:32.290 --> 00:54:37.930
a year and has 10 employees
pays a lot less in tax

00:54:37.930 --> 00:54:40.630
than a company that has a
billion-dollar revenue a year

00:54:40.630 --> 00:54:43.240
and has 1,000 employees,
because of payroll taxes

00:54:43.240 --> 00:54:44.490
and all kinds of other things.

00:54:44.490 --> 00:54:47.350
So there's all kinds of things
we can do to actually encourage

00:54:47.350 --> 00:54:50.020
investing in humans and
employing humans that

00:54:50.020 --> 00:54:52.600
is short of either the universal
basic income or something

00:54:52.600 --> 00:54:53.735
like a robot tax.

00:54:53.735 --> 00:54:55.360
AUDIENCE: I just have
a question that's

00:54:55.360 --> 00:54:57.160
building off one of
the prior answers

00:54:57.160 --> 00:55:02.557
about how we see people
ultimately lean to the right.

00:55:02.557 --> 00:55:04.390
I think, in some of the
texts that I've read

00:55:04.390 --> 00:55:08.170
and so forth, particularly
within the political system

00:55:08.170 --> 00:55:11.620
in the United States, more
of the left-leaning policies

00:55:11.620 --> 00:55:16.300
require a little more research
and a little more understanding

00:55:16.300 --> 00:55:20.140
to see how they can benefit the
population, as opposed to some

00:55:20.140 --> 00:55:21.940
of the more populist
policies that

00:55:21.940 --> 00:55:25.220
feel more visceral for certain
populations and so forth.

00:55:25.220 --> 00:55:29.440
So with this rise of populism
and with this impulse politics

00:55:29.440 --> 00:55:32.770
that is just fundamentally
easier for a lot of people

00:55:32.770 --> 00:55:33.620
to grasp--

00:55:33.620 --> 00:55:35.950
and this question may be too
big for anyone to answer,

00:55:35.950 --> 00:55:38.440
but how do we, as a
country or as a society

00:55:38.440 --> 00:55:42.280
or, as the cautiously
optimistic few that are

00:55:42.280 --> 00:55:43.810
trying to put out the fire--

00:55:43.810 --> 00:55:49.360
work to educate people to see
the benefit of not defaulting

00:55:49.360 --> 00:55:50.616
to impulse?

00:55:50.616 --> 00:55:52.990
YASCHA MOUNK: Why don't I take
both questions, and then--

00:55:52.990 --> 00:55:55.180
AUDIENCE: I was just
wanting to follow up

00:55:55.180 --> 00:55:58.000
on the basic income thing.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:00.710
I understand that there are
two different variants of it

00:56:00.710 --> 00:56:01.210
around.

00:56:01.210 --> 00:56:04.450
One that phases out
as one has a good job,

00:56:04.450 --> 00:56:08.770
and I can easily see how
that would be very insulting.

00:56:08.770 --> 00:56:11.830
What about an actual
universal income,

00:56:11.830 --> 00:56:16.530
where the government sends out
per capita checks to everyone,

00:56:16.530 --> 00:56:18.820
whether they have a job or not?

00:56:18.820 --> 00:56:22.120
YASCHA MOUNK: Yeah,
so I didn't mean--

00:56:22.120 --> 00:56:24.970
I had that in mind, right?

00:56:24.970 --> 00:56:29.950
And I don't mean that it's like,
oh, once you lose your job,

00:56:29.950 --> 00:56:32.350
we're going to help you
and people [INAUDIBLE]..

00:56:32.350 --> 00:56:36.400
I think that's the
big answer, right?

00:56:36.400 --> 00:56:39.640
We assume that 50% of
jobs are going to go away.

00:56:39.640 --> 00:56:42.130
Now, our big answer is, it's OK.

00:56:42.130 --> 00:56:44.710
Like everybody else in society,
you're going to get a check.

00:56:44.710 --> 00:56:48.520
It still basically tells
people that the social distance

00:56:48.520 --> 00:56:51.305
between them and other people
in society is being flattened,

00:56:51.305 --> 00:56:53.180
and they're not going
to be happy about that.

00:56:53.180 --> 00:56:55.600
Now, perhaps that's
the best we can do.

00:56:55.600 --> 00:56:59.312
And we certainly don't have
a claim to feeling better

00:56:59.312 --> 00:57:00.520
than other people in society.

00:57:00.520 --> 00:57:01.840
It's not like there's
a God-given right

00:57:01.840 --> 00:57:02.964
to feel superior to others.

00:57:02.964 --> 00:57:05.441
I'm just saying that I think,
as a political response,

00:57:05.441 --> 00:57:06.940
it's not going to
be very effective.

00:57:06.940 --> 00:57:09.645
Because if you tell people, hey,
I know you're losing your job,

00:57:09.645 --> 00:57:11.020
but don't worry,
everybody inside

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:12.853
is going to get a basic
income and you still

00:57:12.853 --> 00:57:15.670
get to have a
basically decent life,

00:57:15.670 --> 00:57:19.580
I'm going to say, oh, but
I once was somebody, right?

00:57:19.580 --> 00:57:21.780
This is a way of--

00:57:21.780 --> 00:57:28.234
to go back to that intersection
between economics and culture,

00:57:28.234 --> 00:57:29.650
I talked to a
politician who said,

00:57:29.650 --> 00:57:31.900
look, 25 years ago, when I
asked people, who are you,

00:57:31.900 --> 00:57:35.260
in my district, they
said, I'm a Teamster,

00:57:35.260 --> 00:57:39.380
or I'm a steel worker, or I'm a
foreman in the factory, right?

00:57:39.380 --> 00:57:41.750
Today, they don't have that.

00:57:41.750 --> 00:57:43.892
They don't have that
earned identity anymore.

00:57:43.892 --> 00:57:45.850
They don't get the same
belonging and pride out

00:57:45.850 --> 00:57:46.570
of their job.

00:57:46.570 --> 00:57:49.240
And so now when I ask them,
who are you, they might say,

00:57:49.240 --> 00:57:51.000
well, I'm white, and I don't
like those people over there,

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:51.790
right?

00:57:51.790 --> 00:57:54.280
And I fear that
basic income is not

00:57:54.280 --> 00:57:58.000
able to give people an earned
identity in the kind of way

00:57:58.000 --> 00:58:03.520
that pushes them away from
the temptation of that kind

00:58:03.520 --> 00:58:06.400
of ascriptive identity.

00:58:06.400 --> 00:58:11.260
Now, in response to
the other question--

00:58:11.260 --> 00:58:12.970
look, one way of
talking about this

00:58:12.970 --> 00:58:15.490
is that, to me,
the 2016 election

00:58:15.490 --> 00:58:19.120
was a competition between a
moderate politics of the status

00:58:19.120 --> 00:58:22.969
quo and an extremist
politics of change.

00:58:22.969 --> 00:58:25.510
Now, a lot of people vote for
the extremist politic of change

00:58:25.510 --> 00:58:26.770
perhaps because
they're extremists.

00:58:26.770 --> 00:58:29.103
I think, more likely, because
they really wanted change.

00:58:29.103 --> 00:58:32.236
They really wanted a
vision of a better future.

00:58:32.236 --> 00:58:33.610
And so I think
what we need to do

00:58:33.610 --> 00:58:37.359
is to give them a realistic,
non-extremist vision

00:58:37.359 --> 00:58:38.650
of what that future looks like.

00:58:38.650 --> 00:58:41.800
In the end, as long as people
say, the system is screwed

00:58:41.800 --> 00:58:43.810
and nobody cares about
me and there's not

00:58:43.810 --> 00:58:45.484
much for me in
the future anyway,

00:58:45.484 --> 00:58:46.900
they're always
going to be tempted

00:58:46.900 --> 00:58:48.620
by the most extreme people.

00:58:48.620 --> 00:58:52.330
And so what we need to do is to
give people a realistic sense

00:58:52.330 --> 00:58:54.002
that no, you know what?

00:58:54.002 --> 00:58:55.710
If [INAUDIBLE] people
who are [INAUDIBLE]

00:58:55.710 --> 00:58:57.670
[? accept ?] an equal
multi-ethnic society,

00:58:57.670 --> 00:59:00.360
if I do my bit,
then you know what?

00:59:00.360 --> 00:59:04.170
Actually, life is going
to be better for me.

00:59:04.170 --> 00:59:05.920
Politicians do have
something to offer me.

00:59:05.920 --> 00:59:07.687
The system has
something to offer me.

00:59:07.687 --> 00:59:09.520
And that's really hard
work, because there's

00:59:09.520 --> 00:59:12.880
all kinds of complicated reasons
why a system doesn't do it

00:59:12.880 --> 00:59:15.590
effectively at the moment.

00:59:15.590 --> 00:59:18.610
But if we manage to do that,
if we manage to actually

00:59:18.610 --> 00:59:20.811
give people hope
for a better future,

00:59:20.811 --> 00:59:22.810
then I think they're going
to be willing to vote

00:59:22.810 --> 00:59:25.600
for people who can actually
make that possible.

00:59:25.600 --> 00:59:26.800
Thanks.

00:59:26.800 --> 00:59:30.150
[APPLAUSE]

